{{orphan|date=April 2016}} {{Infobox artwork | title = The Virgin and Child with St. Anne | painting_alignment = | other_language_1 = | other_title_1 = | other_language_2 = | other_title_2 = | image = Jan van Steffenswert - Anna-te-Drieën.JPG | image_upright = | alt = The Virgin and Child with St. Anne | caption = | artist = [[Jan van Steffeswert]] | catalogue = | year = 1511 <!-- If after 1583 CE, use {{start date|YYYY}} --> | completion_date = <!-- For a more specific date (post-1583): {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | material = Juglans regia (walnut) | subject = The Virgin and Child with St. Anne | height_metric = 44.2 <!-- (i.e. in metric units) --> | width_metric = | length_metric = | diameter_metric = | height_imperial = <!-- (i.e. in imperial units) --> | width_imperial = | length_imperial = | diameter_imperial = | dimensions = | dimensions_ref = | metric_unit = cm <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included --> | imperial_unit = in <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included --> | condition = | city = [[Maastricht]] | museum = [[Bonnefantenmuseum]] | accession = | coordinates = <!-- Only use for the coordinates (when known) of the artwork itself, i.e. not for the site, building, structure, etc where it is kept, otherwise leave blank (or omit): {{coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} --> | owner = | preceded_by = <!-- preceding work by the same artist --> | followed_by = <!-- next work by the same artist --> | website = <!-- Official webpage/site only: {{URL|example.com}} --> }}
'''The Virgin and Child with St. Anne''' (Dutch: '''Sint Anna te Drieën''') is a sculpture by [[Jan van Steffeswert]] (ca. 1470–1525), a woodcarver from who worked in [[Maastricht]] in the late 15th and early 16th century. Depictions of [[Virgin and Child with Saint Anne| Christ Child with his mother and grandmother]] were popular in the late middle ages. The scene frequently shows Mary and Christ reading. In this scene however, the child is shown grasping a bowl of [[porridge]]. Due to the relatively small size and the emphasis on domesticity, it has been suggested that the sculpture had been commissioned for a home rather than a church. <ref name=Mulder-Bakker>{{Cite book| publisher = Uitgeverij Verloren| isbn = 978-90-6550-996-3| last = Mulder-Bakker| first = Anneke B.| title = Verborgen vrouwen: kluizenaressen in de middeleeuwse stad| date = 2007}}</ref>
Van Steffesweert was one of the first woodcarvers the Meuse region to sign his work.<ref>{{cite web|title=– Jan van Steffenswert : hustinxstichting|url=http://www.hustinxstichting.nl/register/jan-van-steffenswert/|website=www.hustinxstichting.nl|accessdate=28 April 2016}}</ref> This sculpture is simply signed 'IAN'.
